			<h1 class="heading-xlarge">Roadmap</h1>
			<p>This is what we plan to deliver in the coming months, and what we expect to work on over the longer term.</p>
			<p>It’s a guide that’s updated quarterly, and things might change. Get in touch with the team, via <a href="mailto:gov-uk-paas-support@digital.cabinet-office.gov.uk">gov-uk-paas-support@digital.cabinet-office.gov.uk</a>, to find out more about our roadmap and to let us know about features you need.</p>

			<h2 class="heading-medium">January to March 2018</h2>
			<ul class="list list-bullet">
				<li>Backing services (public beta): make Redis, Elasticsearch and MongoDB available for production use</li>
				<li>UK hosting (alpha): create a UK-based GOV.UK PaaS instance and scope the work involved in making this available for production use</li>
				<li>internal-only applications (alpha): explore ways of enabling private, non-internet-facing communication between applications, including service discovery</li>
				<li>GOV.UK PaaS web admin tool (alpha): let users see the platform resources they’re using and manage basic admin tasks themselves</li>
				<li>publish a pricing calculator, so users know how much GOV.UK PaaS will cost them</li>
				<li>improve the support we provide for Docker images</li>
			</ul>

			<h2 class="heading-medium">April 2018 and onwards</h2>
			<ul class="list list-bullet">
				<li>UK-based GOV.UK PaaS (private beta)</li>
				<li>automated billing</li>
				<li>enhanced protective monitoring</li>
				<li>file storage</li>
				<li>metrics for backing services</li>
				<li>improved access control (IP whitelisting/auth)</li>
				<li>RabbitMQ</li>
				<li>Logging as a Service</li>
			</ul>

			<h2 class="heading-medium">Longer term possibilities</h2>
			<ul class="list list-bullet">
				<li>PSN connectivity</li>
				<li>CDN as a Service</li>
				<li>CI as a Service</li>
				<li>Memcache</li>
				<li>VM isolation, dependent on Cloud Foundry upstream developments</li>
			</ul>
			
			<h2 class="heading-medium">Development stages</h2>
			<p>Most of the features we’re building go through the following stages of development:</p>
			<ul class="list list-bullet">
				<li>alpha: exploring the problem space and investigating possible solutions</li>
				<li>private beta: an early working version of the feature that’s tested by selected partners in a development environment - not suitable for use in production</li>
				<li>public beta: a production-ready version of the feature that has been subjected to Cabinet Office/GDS information approval and security governance</li>
				<li>live: a production-ready service that has been improved based on feedback during public beta</li>
			</ul>
